"analysis": "From the previous summary: global P95 thresholds for many component-KPI series were computed (metric groups commonly have 31 points spanning timestamps 1616504400–1616506200). trace.csv groups are sparse (mostly single points). log.error_count P95 is 0 for Tomcat hosts and error_logs.csv has 0 rows. This indicates: metric data covers the requested time range (so we can detect metric anomalies there), traces are sparse but available (can be used later to disambiguate), and error logs contain no entries. Next we should perform anomaly detection on metrics inside the failure window (March 23, 2021 21:00–21:30 UTC+8) using the already computed global thresholds. Specifically, for each candidate component-KPI (candidate components: apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02) we should: 1) compute counts of points within the window, 2) count how many points exceed global P95 (value >= P95) and how many fall below global P05 (value <= P05), 3) report earliest timestamp of any breach (>=P95 or <=P05), and 4) report the max and min values observed in the window. This will narrow candidate faulty component-KPIs for the next steps.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Using metric.csv, perform the following (Executor should handle timestamp parsing with timezone UTC+8 and use global thresholds computed from the full series per component-KPI):\n1) Restrict analysis to these candidate components only: apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02.\n2) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair among those components, compute global P95 and global P05 from the full available metric series (do NOT compute thresholds after filtering). Then filter metric rows into the incident window: 2021-03-23 21:00:00 to 2021-03-23 21:30:00 (UTC+8).\n3) For each group, return these compact columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_points_in_window, count_ge_P95_in_window, count_le_P05_in_window, earliest_ts_ge_P95 (or null), earliest_ts_le_P05 (or null), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, P95_global, P05_global.\n4) Limit output to top 20 rows sorted by count_ge_P95_in_window desc, then count_le_P05_in_window desc. If there are ties, sort by count_points_in_window desc. Keep output as a compact table (at most 20 rows)."
