"instruction": "From metric.csv, identify (cmdb_id, kpi_name) groups where global_P95 != global_P05 (compute P95 and P05 from the full series before filtering). Then filter rows to the incident window 2021-03-23 21:00:00 → 2021-03-23 21:30:00 (UTC+8). For each group that has at least one point in-window, compute and return a compact table (limit to top 20 rows) with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_points_in_window, count_ge_P95_in_window, count_le_P05_in_window, earliest_ts_ge_P95 (or null), earliest_ts_le_P05 (or null), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, P95_global, P05_global. Sort rows by count_ge_P95_in_window desc, then count_le_P05_in_window desc, then count_points_in_window desc. Return only the table (text/CSV-formatted) and keep output compact."
}

{
"analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and multiple rounds of metric thresholding (P95/P05 and P90/P10). Findings so far: most allowed-component metrics are constant (P95==P05) and not informative. Trace data for allowed components in the incident window is absent. Logs show Tomcat/Apache activity but error_count is zero (no obvious error spikes). The one clear signal among allowed components is Mysql02: the metric 'Mysql-MySQL_3306_Open Tables' shows persistently high values in the window (most minutes == 2474.0, global P95 = 2474.0, many in-window points >= P95, earliest >=P95 at timestamp 1616504400). This suggests a sustained abnormal DB state during the window, making Mysql02 the primary fault candidate. To localize the root cause reason we need corroborating metrics for Mysql02 (CPU, memory, disk, I/O) to see which resource is stressed. Next, we should enumerate Mysql02's available metric KPIs and their global P95/P05 to identify any other anomalous KPIs to confirm the underlying reason (e.g., high CPU, high memory, high disk I/O).",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "From metric.csv, restrict to cmdb_id == 'Mysql02'. Aggregate by kpi_name and for each group compute: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_of_points (over full file), global_P95_value, global_P05_value, min_timestamp, max_timestamp. Return a compact table limited to top 50 rows sorted by count_of_points desc. This will list all available Mysql02 KPIs and their global thresholds so we can identify additional stressed resources to explain the high 'Open Tables' metric."
}

{
"analysis": "We have followed preprocess and metric analysis: global thresholds (P95/P05 and P90/P10) were computed for all component-KPIs. Most allowed components show constant series (P95==P05), making quantile thresholding ineffective. Trace data for allowed components in the window is absent. Logs show no error spikes (Tomcat/Apache error_count P95 = 0). The strongest signal among allowed components is Mysql02: 'Mysql-MySQL_3306_Open Tables' is persistently high during the window (most minutes == 2474.0, global P95 = 2474.0, earliest >=P95 at timestamp 1616504400). Mysql02 also exposes many IO/InnoDB-related KPIs with very large global P95 values in the full series, suggesting DB IO or buffer-pool stress that could explain elevated open table counts. We need to confirm which Mysql02 KPIs exhibit contiguous anomaly segments in the incident window (using global thresholds computed from full series) to localize the fault start time and the most deviated resource (CPU/memory/disk/IO/connection). This step will produce concrete fault segments to support root-cause localization.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "For metric.csv, restrict to cmdb_id == 'Mysql02'. For each kpi_name: 1) compute global_P95 and global_P05 from the full series (do NOT compute thresholds after filtering). 2) Filter rows to the incident window 2021-03-23 21:00:00 → 2021-03-23 21:30:00 (UTC+8). 3) Identify contiguous anomaly segments in-window where consecutive timestamps differ by 60 seconds: HIGH segments where value >= global_P95, and LOW segments where value <= global_P05. 4) For each segment return one row with columns: kpi_name, anomaly_type ('HIGH'/'LOW'), start_ts, end_ts, duration_points, max_value_in_segment, min_value_in_segment, P95_global, P05_global. 5) Return a compact table limited to top 20 segments sorted by duration_points desc. Also return the single earliest_segment_start_ts_overall with its kpi_name and anomaly_type (the minimum start_ts among all segments). If no segments found, explicitly return the text: 'no anomaly segments found for Mysql02 in window'. Keep output compact."
}

